Objectives / Learning Outcome(s) / Major:
THE STUDENT WILL BE ABLE TO:
1.IDENTIFY, MEASURE AND COMMUNICATE ECONOMIC INFORMATION THROUGH THE PROCESS OF ACCOUNTING;
2.INTERPRET AND EXPLAIN FINANCIAL STATEMENTS PREPARED ACCORDING TO GAAP (GENERALLY ACCEPTED ACCOUNTING PRINCIPLES);
3.APPLY FINANCIAL ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS AND PRINCIPLES AS DIRECTED BY THE FASB (FINANCIAL ACCOUNTING STANDARDS BOARD);
4.EXPLAIN THE SARBANES-OXLEY ACT OF 2002 AND ITS IMPACT ON BUSINESS AND ACCOUNTING;
5.READ AN ANNUAL REPORT AND EXTRACT DATA PERTAINING TO ACCOUNTING CONCEPTS AND OBJECTIVES;
6.PREPARE THE FINANCIAL STATEMENTS REQUIRED BY PUBLICLY HELD COMPANIES;
7.COMPLETE ALL STEPS IN THE ACCOUNTING CYCLE INCLUDING ADJUSTING AND CLOSING ENTRIES;
8.COMPUTE ENDING INVENTORY AND COST OF GOODS SOLD USING APPROVED ACCOUNTING METHODS;
9.EXPLAIN THE COMPONENTS OF INTERNAL CONTROLS;
10.EXPLAIN AND PERFORM CONTROLS OVER CASH;
11.RECORD TRANSACTIONS AND MAINTAIN ACCOUNTS FOR LONG  INVESTMENTS AND RECEIVABLES;
12.COMPUTE THE COST AND RECORD THE TRANSACTIONS FOR OPERATING ASSETS;
13.COMPUTE AND RECORD THE SYSTEMATIC AND RELATIONAL ALLOCATION OF OPERATING ASSETS;
14.PREPARE APPROPRIATE JOURNAL ENTRIES FOR CURRENT AND LONG-TERM LIABILITIES AND CONTINGENCIES;
15.COMPUTE THE TIME VALUE OF MONEY;
16.PREPARE, INTERPRET AND EXPLAIN THE COMPONENTS OF STOCKHOLDERS EQUITY; AND
17.EVALUATE COMPANIES LIQUIDITY, PROFITABILITY, AND SOLVENCY USING RATIO ANALYSIS, HORIZONTAL AND VERTICAL ANALYSIS.
